Resize the images¶

Introduction to Computer Vision: Plant Seedlings Classification¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

In recent times, the field of agriculture has been in urgent need of modernizing, since the amount of manual work people need to put in to check if plants are growing correctly is still highly extensive. Despite several advances in agricultural technology, people working in the agricultural industry still need to have the ability to sort and recognize different plants and weeds, which takes a lot of time and effort in the long term. The potential is ripe for this trillion-dollar industry to be greatly impacted by technological innovations that cut down on the requirement for manual labor, and this is where Artificial Intelligence can actually benefit the workers in this field, as the time and energy required to identify plant seedlings will be greatly shortened by the use of AI and Deep Learning. The ability to do so far more efficiently and even more effectively than experienced manual labor, could lead to better crop yields, the freeing up of human inolvement for higher-order agricultural decision making, and in the long term will result in more sustainable environmental practices in agriculture as well.

Objective¶

The aim of this project is to Build a Convolutional Neural Netowrk to classify plant seedlings into their respective categories.

Data Dictionary¶

The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with the University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 different species.

  • The dataset can be download from Olympus.
  • The data file names are:
    • images.npy
    • Labels.csv

  • Due to the large volume of data, the images were converted to the images.npy file and the labels are also put into Labels.csv, so that you can work on the data/project seamlessly without having to worry about the high data volume.

  • The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from an image.

List of Species

  • Black-grass
  • Charlock
  • Cleavers
  • Common Chickweed
  • Common Wheat
  • Fat Hen
  • Loose Silky-bent
  • Maize
  • Scentless Mayweed
  • Shepherds Purse
  • Small-flowered Cranesbill
  • Sugar beet

Data Pre-Processing¶

Convert the BGR images to RGB images.¶

In [20]:
#covert the bgr images to rgb images
images = images[:, :, :, ::-1]

Resize the images¶

As the size of the images is large, it may be computationally expensive to train on these larger images; therefore, it is preferable to reduce the image size from 128 to 64.

In [21]:
import cv2

resized_images = []
for img in images:
    resized_img = cv2.resize(img, (64, 64))
    resized_images.append(resized_img)

resized_images = np.array(resized_images)

Data Preparation for Modeling¶

  • Before you proceed to build a model, you need to split the data into train, test, and validation to be able to evaluate the model that you build on the train data
  • You'll have to encode categorical features and scale the pixel values.
  • You will build a model using the train data and then check its performance

label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
encoded_labels = label_encoder.fit_transform(labels['Label'])  # 'Label' is the correct column name

# Convert encoded labels to one-hot format
labels = to_categorical(encoded_labels, num_classes=len(np.unique(encoded_labels)))

Model Building¶

In [34]:
# Step 6: Model Architecture
model = Sequential()

# First Convolutional Block
model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 3)))  # Input shape adjusted to (128, 128, 3)
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

# Second Convolutional Block
model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

# Third Convolutional Block
model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

# Flatten Layer
model.add(Flatten())  # Flattening the output from the convolutional blocks

# Fully Connected Layers
model.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))  # Output layer with 12 classes

# Compile the Model
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Callbacks
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', factor=0.2, patience=5)

# Model Summary
model.summary()

Model Performance Improvement¶

Reducing the Learning Rate:

Hint: Use ReduceLRonPlateau() function that will be used to decrease the learning rate by some factor, if the loss is not decreasing for some time. This may start decreasing the loss at a smaller learning rate. There is a possibility that the loss may still not decrease. This may lead to executing the learning rate reduction again in an attempt to achieve a lower loss.

Data Augmentation¶

Remember, data augmentation should not be used in the validation/test data set.

Final Model¶

Comment on the final model you have selected and use the same in the below code to visualize the image.

In [35]:
# Required Imports
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Flatten, Dense, Dropout, BatchNormalization
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from tensorflow.keras.utils import to_categorical
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ReduceLROnPlateau
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming images and labels are already loaded and preprocessed as follows:
# images = ... (loaded from images.npy)
# labels_df = ... (loaded from Labels.csv)
# encoded_labels = ... (label encoding process)
# labels = ... (one-hot encoding process)
# Normalize the images
images = images / 255.0  # Scale pixel values to [0, 1]

# Step 4: Split the data into train, validation, and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(images, labels, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X_train, y_train, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Step 5: Data Augmentation Setup
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rotation_range=20,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    fill_mode='nearest'
)

# Fit the generator to the training data
datagen.fit(X_train)

# Step 6: Model Architecture
model = Sequential()

# First Convolutional Block
model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 3)))  # Input shape
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

# Second Convolutional Block
model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

# Third Convolutional Block
model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

# Flatten Layer
model.add(Flatten())  # Flattening the output from the convolutional blocks

# Fully Connected Layers
model.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))  # Output layer with 12 classes

# Compile the Model
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Callbacks
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', factor=0.2, patience=5, verbose=1)

# Model Summary
model.summary()

# Model Training with Data Augmentation and Learning Rate Reduction
history = model.fit(datagen.flow(X_train, y_train, batch_size=32),
                    validation_data=(X_val, y_val),
                    epochs=50,
                    callbacks=[early_stopping, reduce_lr])

# Optional: Function to visualize images
def plot_images(images, labels, num=5):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    for i in range(num):
        plt.subplot(1, num, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(images[i])
        plt.title(label_encoder.inverse_transform([np.argmax(labels[i])])[0])  # Convert back to original label
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

# Display some training images
plot_images(X_train, y_train)

Model: "sequential_4"

Visualizing the prediction¶

In [36]:
# Function to visualize predictions
def visualize_predictions(model, X_test, y_test, num_images=5):
    # Generate predictions
    predictions = model.predict(X_test)

    # Select a random subset of images
    indices = np.random.choice(len(X_test), num_images, replace=False)

    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    for i, index in enumerate(indices):
        plt.subplot(1, num_images, i + 1)

        # Display the image
        plt.imshow(X_test[index])

        # Get the predicted and actual labels
        predicted_label = np.argmax(predictions[index])
        actual_label = np.argmax(y_test[index])

        # Convert back to original label
        predicted_label_name = label_encoder.inverse_transform([predicted_label])[0]
        actual_label_name = label_encoder.inverse_transform([actual_label])[0]

        plt.title(f"Pred: {predicted_label_name}\nActual: {actual_label_name}")
        plt.axis('off')

    plt.show()

# Visualize predictions on the test set
visualize_predictions(model, X_test, y_test, num_images=5)

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Actionable Insights Model Performance:

Accuracy Metrics: Assess the model's accuracy on the validation and test sets. A high accuracy (e.g., above 85%) indicates that the model is effective in classifying the plant species. Loss Analysis: Track the loss values during training to identify overfitting or underfitting. If the validation loss is significantly higher than the training loss, it may indicate overfitting. Predictive Patterns:

Common Misclassifications: Analyze which species are most commonly misclassified. Understanding these misclassifications can highlight similarities in plant characteristics that may confuse the model. Feature Importance:

Visualize Features: Use techniques like Grad-CAM or saliency maps to understand which features of the images (e.g., leaf shape, color) contribute most to the predictions. This could help in refining the model or identifying key characteristics of different species. Data Augmentation Impact:

Evaluate Augmentation Effects: Determine the effect of data augmentation on model performance. Analyze whether augmenting the dataset helped improve the model’s generalization capabilities. Business Recommendations Enhancing Model Training:

Continuous Model Improvement: Regularly retrain the model with new data to improve its accuracy. Incorporate user feedback to identify areas of improvement and expand the dataset with more examples, especially for misclassified species. Integration into Applications:

Develop an Application: Create a user-friendly application or tool that utilizes the model for real-time plant species identification. This could be targeted toward gardening enthusiasts, botanists, or agricultural workers. Education and Awareness:

User Education: Provide educational content alongside the application, helping users understand plant characteristics, care tips, and potential uses. This could enhance user engagement and satisfaction. Market Targeting:

Identify Target Users: Focus on specific user groups such as horticulturists, landscape architects, or environmental researchers who may benefit from accurate plant identification and insights into plant health. Strategic Partnerships:

Collaborate with Botanical Gardens and Research Institutions: Partner with organizations to collect more diverse data, validate the model’s predictions, and explore practical applications in conservation efforts. Feedback Loop:

Implement a Feedback Mechanism: Allow users to provide feedback on the accuracy of the predictions. This feedback can be invaluable for refining the model over time. Conclusion By leveraging the insights gained from model training and predictions, organizations can enhance their decision-making processes, improve customer engagement, and develop innovative solutions in plant species identification. Regularly revisiting and refining the model based on new data and user feedback will ensure that the system remains robust and effective in meeting user needs.
